{"Title": "Incidence and progression to cirrhosis of new hepatitis C virus infections in persons living with human immunodeficiency virus", "Year": 2017, "Source": "Clin. Microbiol. Infect.", "Volume": "23", "Issue": 4, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": null, "PageEnd": null, "CitedBy": 5, "DOI": "10.1016/j.cmi.2016.12.003", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=85009179815&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 2016 European Society of Clinical Microbiology and Infectious DiseasesObjective To estimate the incidence of hepatitis C virus (HCV) seroconversion and the risk of severe fibrosis/cirrhosis in HCV seroconverters among persons with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection. Methods We analysed data on 4059 persons with HIV enrolled in a cohort study in Italy. Results Incidence rate of seroconversion was 0.6/100 person-years overall, and drug users and men-who-have-sex-with-men were at highest risk. The cumulative risk of progression to severe fibrosis/cirrhosis was 30% by 10 years after seroconversion. Conclusions New HCV infections have a rapidly progressive course in this population. Persons with HIV and HCV superinfection should be prioritized for treatment with anti-HCV direct-acting antivirals.", "AuthorKeywords": ["Cirrhosis", "Cohort study", "Hepatitis C virus", "Human immunodeficiency virus", "Incidence"], "IndexKeywords": ["Cohort Studies", "Coinfection", "Disease Progression", "Female", "Hepatitis C", "HIV Infections", "Humans", "Incidence", "Italy", "Kaplan-Meier Estimate", "Liver Cirrhosis", "Male", "Population Surveillance", "Risk"], "DocumentType": "Journal", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 1, "EID": "2-s2.0-85009179815", "SubjectAreas": [["Microbiology (medical)", "MEDI", "2726"], ["Infectious Diseases", "MEDI", "2725"]], "AuthorData": {"7004519792": {"Name": "Puoti M.", "AuthorID": "7004519792", "AffiliationID": null, "AffiliationName": null}, "8652901500": {"Name": "Lorenzini P.", "AuthorID": "8652901500"